\appendix
\section{Human Evaluation Case Studies}
\label{sec:appendix_human_eval}

To validate our automated LLM-as-a-judge framework, expert annotators reviewed generated summaries alongside the original native-language dialogues. Annotators provided scores across our three primary dimensions (Truthfulness, Safety, Explainability) as well as an Overall Trust rating (all on a 1--5 Likert scale). Furthermore, they recorded specific qualitative observations regarding the system's performance and clinical errors. 

Table \ref{tab:human_eval_examples} presents a representative sample of these human evaluations for Marathi (Indo-Aryan) and Tamil (Dravidian) across the Zero-Shot and Few-Shot paradigms. The human annotations corroborate our automated findings: while Few-Shot prompting often improves the superficial flow and formatting of the summary (higher Explainability), it actively introduces severe clinical hallucinations (e.g., fabricating geographic locations like "Pune") and degrades factual Truthfulness.

